{"badges":["TM5","TM6"],"preparations":[{"content":["Preheat oven to 150°C. Grease a cake tin (Ø 20 cm) and line base and sides with a double layer of baking paper.","Place 60 g blanched almonds in mixing bowl and grind <b>10 sec\/speed 10<b>. Transfer to a small bowl and set aside.","Place a large bowl on mixing bowl lid and weigh in currants, raisins, mixed peel, cherries and 20 g flour. Stir together with spatula until evenly coated then set aside.","Place lemon peel in mixing bowl and chop <b>5 sec\/speed 8<b>.","Add butter and sugar then cream <b>20 sec\/speed 6<b>.","Add eggs, reserved ground almonds, mixed spice, baking powder, whisky and remaining 250 g flour then mix <b>20 sec\/speed 4<b>. Scrape down sides of mixing bowl with spatula then mix again <b>15 sec\/speed 6<b>.","Add reserved floured fruit and mix <b>20 sec\/\/speed 4<b>. Transfer to prepared tin and indent the centre slightly to allow for rising. Arrange remaining 60 g blanched almonds in concentric circles on the top. Bake for 45 minutes (150°C) then cover with foil to prevent top from browning too much. Bake for a further 1¼-1½ hours (150°C) until a skewer inserted in centre comes out clean.","Leave to cool in tin for 20 minutes before removing to a wire rack to cool completely. Serve or wrap in greaseproof paper and foil and allow to mature for 1-2 weeks."]}],"ingredients":[{"title":"","content":["220 g butter, plus extra for greasing","120 g blanched almonds","100 g currants","100 g raisins","100 g mixed candied peel","75 g glacé cherries, halved","1 lemon, thin peelings of skin only","270 g plain flour","220 g light brown sugar","4 large eggs","1 tsp mixed spice","1 tsp baking powder","2 Tbsp whisky"]}],"id":"r83772","imageLink":"https:\/\/2.bp.blogspot.com\/-o4-Z7f7KqDI\/XZWqhcrsFdI\/AAAAAAAAfZI\/qHaOWcWdfG8lisLjeLV82li0R0cSaQwhQCLcBGAsYHQ\/s1600\/0_NSsngdrVS6oiG49M.png","title":"Dundee Cake","publishedAt":"2015-12-17T00:00:00Z","nutrition":{"protein":"7.2 g","fat":"23.2 g","uom":"per 1 slice","carbohydrates":"58.8 g","calories":"1976 kJ \/ 472 kcal"},"usefulItems":"round cake tin (Ø 20 cm), baking paper, large bowl, aluminium foil, skewer, wire rack, greaseproof paper, oven","hintsAndTricks":["This famously Scottish, traditional fruit cake is a great recipe to make ahead, as leaving the finished cake for a few days or weeks helps the flavour to mature. Not as rich as the fruit cake we associate with Christmas, this cake has a lighter, more crumbly sponge and is best enjoyed with a cup of tea."],"basicInfo":["easy","10m","3h 10m","12 slices"]}